Terms, definitions and coding schemas (partial)
Purpose (? discourse studies ?)

Internal system:
First&nbsp;element&nbsp;(enabler) = (1)
Second&nbsp;element&nbsp;and/or top&nbsp;category = (2)&nbsp;
Some&nbsp;elements&nbsp;can&nbsp;appear&nbsp;out of the&nbsp;sequence&nbsp;they&nbsp;present&nbsp;(p.67).&nbsp;

Method:&nbsp;Used&nbsp;ENNI = a set of&nbsp;picture&nbsp;stories&nbsp;based&nbsp;on Stein &amp;&nbsp;Glenn's&nbsp;1979 (?).
This set was chosen because it was already used to study Canadien children in English &amp; French, hence&nbsp;it&nbsp;would&nbsp;permit&nbsp;some&nbsp;cross-linguistic&nbsp;and cross-cultural&nbsp;comparison.&nbsp;Kuwaiti Arabicp.4&nbsp;describes&nbsp;the&nbsp;coding. It&nbsp;was&nbsp;done&nbsp;using&nbsp;the ENNI&nbsp;scoring&nbsp;criteria&nbsp;with&nbsp;slight&nbsp;modifications.&nbsp;Each&nbsp;telling&nbsp;gets&nbsp;a single score&nbsp;based&nbsp;on&nbsp;its&nbsp;degree&nbsp;of&nbsp;completeness&nbsp;Findings:&nbsp;&nbsp;
p.6-7: Story&nbsp;complexity&nbsp;increased&nbsp;with&nbsp;age&nbsp;but&nbsp;didn't&nbsp;meet&nbsp;the&nbsp;adult&nbsp;benchmark.&nbsp;Results&nbsp;with&nbsp;Kuwaiti&nbsp;children&nbsp;are comparable to&nbsp;results&nbsp;of&nbsp;study&nbsp;done&nbsp;with&nbsp;Canadian&nbsp;children,&nbsp;suggesting&nbsp;ENNI&nbsp;is&nbsp;suitable&nbsp;for adaptation&nbsp;across&nbsp;languages&nbsp;and cultures.&nbsp;&nbsp;
p.7:&nbsp;Children&nbsp;had&nbsp;similar&nbsp;scores&nbsp;when&nbsp;telling&nbsp;simple and&nbsp;complex&nbsp;stories&nbsp;alike,&nbsp;whereas&nbsp;adults' score&nbsp;showed&nbsp;a&nbsp;difference&nbsp;(better&nbsp;performance on simple stories).&nbsp;&nbsp;
p.8:&nbsp;Children&nbsp;and&nbsp;adults&nbsp;were&nbsp;more&nbsp;likely&nbsp;to&nbsp;include&nbsp;core&nbsp;elements&nbsp;than&nbsp;complementary&nbsp;ones,&nbsp;which&nbsp;is&nbsp;in line&nbsp;with&nbsp;previous&nbsp;research&nbsp;in&nbsp;other&nbsp;languages.&nbsp;&nbsp;
p.9: No&nbsp;effect&nbsp;of story&nbsp;complexity&nbsp;found.&nbsp;Core&nbsp;macrostructure&nbsp;elements&nbsp;were&nbsp;mastered&nbsp;before&nbsp;complementary&nbsp;ones.&nbsp;&nbsp;
p.2-3.&nbsp;Arabic&nbsp;is&nbsp;highly&nbsp;diglossic.&nbsp;Imo,&nbsp;authors&nbsp;tell&nbsp;little&nbsp;about the&nbsp;consequences&nbsp;on&nbsp;expected&nbsp;results&nbsp;or&nbsp;study&nbsp;design.&nbsp;They&nbsp;point out&nbsp;that&nbsp;each&nbsp;Arabic&nbsp;dialect&nbsp;requires&nbsp;different&nbsp;assessment&nbsp;tools, and on p.8,&nbsp;that&nbsp;research&nbsp;needs&nbsp;to focus on&nbsp;spoken&nbsp;dialects&nbsp;&amp; storytelling practices at home.&nbsp; Story&nbsp;Grammar&nbsp;model&nbsp;
p. 5-6: the model&nbsp;used&nbsp;involve&nbsp;Core&nbsp;VS&nbsp;complementary&nbsp;story&nbsp;grammar.&nbsp;&nbsp; Core&nbsp;=&nbsp;initiating&nbsp;event&nbsp;+&nbsp;attempt&nbsp;(main&nbsp;character's&nbsp;response&nbsp;to the&nbsp;initiating&nbsp;event) +&nbsp;outcome&nbsp;(consequences&nbsp;of the&nbsp;attempt).&nbsp;&nbsp;
Complementary&nbsp;= setting +&nbsp;characters&nbsp;+&nbsp;reactions&nbsp;(characters' feelings or&nbsp;thoughts&nbsp;about&nbsp;outcomes). All&nbsp;age&nbsp;groups&nbsp;were&nbsp;more&nbsp;likely&nbsp;to&nbsp;include&nbsp;core&nbsp;elements&nbsp;than&nbsp;complementary&nbsp;elements.&nbsp; p.9: The&nbsp;tendency&nbsp;to&nbsp;exclude&nbsp;internal&nbsp;states (among&nbsp;children&nbsp;and&nbsp;adults)&nbsp;might&nbsp;be&nbsp;a cultural&nbsp;difference.&nbsp;&nbsp;
p.10: 'Internal&nbsp;plan', 'internal&nbsp;response' and 'reaction' do not&nbsp;seem&nbsp;like essential&nbsp;elements&nbsp;of stories of&nbsp;adults,&nbsp;because&nbsp;they&nbsp;often&nbsp;excluded&nbsp;them,&nbsp;whereas&nbsp;they&nbsp;always&nbsp;included&nbsp;'setting' and 'characters'. This&nbsp;finding&nbsp;is&nbsp;specific&nbsp;to&nbsp;this&nbsp;study, and not&nbsp;reflected&nbsp;in the&nbsp;study&nbsp;on Canadian&nbsp;children.&nbsp;So the notion of&nbsp;core&nbsp;and&nbsp;complementary&nbsp;elements&nbsp;needs&nbsp;revision&nbsp;(to&nbsp;account&nbsp;for cultural&nbsp;differences).

This is a reconstruction; the description of the coding schema is scattered and incomplete.Transcription&nbsp;is&nbsp;divided&nbsp;into&nbsp;clauses.&nbsp;
All clauses are labelled.
A subset of verbs are labelled (+), which results in labelling all verbs (+/-).
